==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic: cognate with Old High German [[uohta]], Old Norse [[ótta]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ˈu:xta/}}

===Noun===
{{Unicode|'''ūhta'''}} ''m'' (plural {{Unicode|[[uhtan|ūhtan]]}})
# the time just before the dawn, the last part of night
#:''Cymð on uhtan easterne wind'': the east wind comes before dawn.
# the time or service of [[nocturns]]

